# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boulder-batholith
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] A **batholith** (from Ancient Greek βαθύς (*bathús*), meaning "deep", and λίθος (*líthos*), meaning "stone") is a large mass of intrusive igneous rock (also called plutonic rock), larger than 100 km2 (40 sq mi) in area, that forms from cooled magma deep in the Earth's crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Batholiths are almost always made mostly of felsic or intermediate rock types, such as granite, quartz monzonite, or diorite (see also *granite dome*).
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Although they may appear uniform, batholiths are in fact structures with complex histories and compositions.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] They are composed of multiple masses, or *plutons*, bodies of igneous rock of irregular dimensions (typically at least several kilometers) that can be distinguished from adjacent igneous rock by some combination of criteria including age, composition, texture, or mappable structures.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Individual plutons are solidified from magma that traveled toward the surface from a zone of partial melting near the base of the Earth's crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Traditionally, these plutons have been considered to form by ascent of relatively buoyant magma in large masses called *plutonic diapirs*.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Because the diapirs are liquified and very hot, they tend to rise through the surrounding native country rock, pushing it aside and partially melting it.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Most diapirs do not reach the surface to form volcanoes, but instead they slow down, cool, and usually solidify 5 to 30 kilometers underground as plutons (hence the use of the word *pluton*; in reference to the Roman god of the underworld Pluto).
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] An alternate view is that plutons are formed by aggregation of smaller volumes of magma that ascend as dikes.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] A batholith is formed when many plutons converge to form a huge expanse of granitic rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Some batholiths are mammoth, paralleling past and present subduction zones and other heat sources for hundreds of kilometers in continental crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] One such batholith is the Sierra Nevada Batholith, which is a continuous granitic formation that makes up much of the Sierra Nevada in California.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] An even larger batholith, the Coast Plutonic Complex, is found predominantly in the Coast Mountains of western Canada; it extends for 1,800 kilometers and reaches into southeastern Alaska.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] A batholith is an exposed area of (mostly) continuous plutonic rock that covers an area larger than 100 square kilometers (40 square miles).
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Areas smaller than 100 square kilometers are called *stocks*.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] However, the majority of batholiths visible at the surface (via outcroppings) have areas far greater than 100 square kilometers.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] These areas are exposed to the surface through the process of erosion accelerated by continental uplift acting over many tens of millions to hundreds of millions of years.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] This process has removed several tens of square kilometers of overlying rock in many areas, exposing the once deeply buried batholiths.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] Batholiths exposed at the surface are subjected to huge pressure differences between their former location deep in the earth and their new location at or near the surface.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] As a result, their crystal structure expands slightly over time.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] This manifests itself by a form of mass wasting called exfoliation.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] This form of weathering causes convex and relatively thin sheets of rock to slough off the exposed surfaces of batholiths (a process accelerated by frost wedging).
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] The result is fairly clean and rounded rock faces.
[src:boulder-batholith/batholith] A well-known result of this process is Half Dome in Yosemite Valley.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The **Boulder Batholith** is a relatively small batholith in southwestern Montana, United States, exposed at the surface as granite (more specifically quartz monzonite) and serving as the host rock for rich mineralized deposits at Butte and other locations.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The batholith lies roughly between Butte and Helena, and between the Deer Lodge (Upper Clark Fork) Valley and the Broadwater (Upper Missouri) Valley.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The volcanic Elkhorn Mountains are a large mass of forested lava associated with the batholith.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The batholith is composed of at least seven, and possibly as many as 14, discrete rock masses called plutons, which had formed beneath the Earth's surface during a period of magma intrusion about 73 to 78 million years ago (Late Cretaceous time).
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The rising buoyant plutons resulted from subduction along what was then the west coast of North America, which was near today's border between Montana and Idaho.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] Regional uplift brought the deep-seated granite to the surface, where erosion exposed the rocks and the extremely rich mineral veins they contained.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] Hundreds of millions of dollars of copper, silver, gold, zinc, lead, and other metals have been mined from the batholith, both using underground mining and pit mining.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The Butte Granite makes up the bulk of the batholith (about 70%), with additional named intrusions along the periphery consisting of granodiorite, monzogranite, and minor syenogranite.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The batholith intruded into Mesoproterozoic and Mesozoic sedimentary rocks, including the Elkhorn Mountains volcanics.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The origin of these igneous rocks is related to subduction and continental magmatic arc processes associated with the Late Cretaceous western margin of North America.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] Later hydrothermal vein activity along fault and shear zones within the Butte quartz monzonite and its contact with adjacent rocks, resulted in major ore deposits of lead, zinc, and silver.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] The Boulder Batholith was named for the prominent rounded boulders that typify its landscape, the result of spheroidal weathering of fractured granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/boulder-batholith] It measures approximately 75 miles (121 km) north-south by about 25 miles (40 km) east-west, rather small in comparison to most batholiths.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Established in 1864 as a mining camp in the northern Rocky Mountains on the Continental Divide, Butte experienced rapid development in the late 19th century, and was Montana's first major industrial city.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In its heyday between the late 19th and early 20th centuries, it was one of the largest copper boom towns in the American West.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Employment opportunities in the mines attracted surges of European and Asian immigrants, particularly the Irish; as of 2017, Butte has the largest population of Irish Americans per capita of any U.S. city.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte was also the site of various historical events involving its mining industry and active labor unions and socialist politics, the most famous of which was the labor riot of 1914.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Despite the dominance of the Anaconda Copper Mining Company, Butte was never a company town.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Other major events in the city's history include the 1917 Speculator Mine disaster, the largest hard rock mining disaster in world history.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the late 20th century, the EPA instated cleanup efforts, and the Butte Citizens Technical Environmental Committee was established in 1984.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the 21st century, efforts to interpret and preserve Butte's heritage are addressing both the town's historical significance and the continuing importance of mining to its economy and culture.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city's Uptown Historic District, on the National Register of Historic Places, is one of the largest National Historic Landmark Districts in the U.S., containing nearly 6,000 contributing properties.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city is also home to Montana Technological University, a public engineering and technical university.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Before Butte's formal establishment in 1864, the area consisted of a mining camp that had developed in the early 1860s.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city is in the Silver Bow Creek Valley (or Summit Valley), a natural bowl sitting high in the Rockies straddling the Continental Divide, positioned on the southwestern side of a large mass of granite known as the Boulder Batholith, which dates to the Cretaceous era.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Farlin founded the Asteroid Mine (subsequently known as the Travona), which attracted a significant number of prospectors seeking gold and silver.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The mines attracted workers from Cornwall (England), Ireland, Wales, Lebanon, Canada, Finland, Austria, Italy, China, Montenegro, Mexico, and more.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the ethnic neighborhoods, young men formed gangs to protect their territory and socialize into adult life, including the Irish of Dublin Gulch, the Eastern Europeans of the McQueen Addition, and the Italians of Meaderville.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Among the migrants were many Chinese who set up businesses that created a Chinatown in Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Chinese migrations stopped in 1882 with the passage of the Chinese Exclusion Act.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] There was anti-Chinese sentiment in the 1870s and onward, exacerbated by economic depression, and in 1895, the chamber of commerce and labor unions started a boycott of Chinese-owned businesses.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The business owners fought back by suing the unions and won.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The history of the Chinese migrants in Butte is documented in the Mai Wah Museum.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The influx of miners gave Butte a reputation as a wide-open town where any vice was obtainable.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city's saloon and red-light district, called the "Line" or "The Copper Block", centered on Mercury Street, where the elegant bordellos included the famous Dumas Brothel.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Commercial breweries first opened in Butte in the 1870s, and were a staple of the city's early economy; they were usually run by German immigrants, including Leopold Schmidt, Henry Mueller, and Henry Muntzer.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The breweries were always staffed by union workers.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Most ethnic groups in Butte, from Germans and Irish to Italians and various Eastern Europeans, including children, enjoyed the locally brewed lagers, bocks, and other types of beer.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the late 19th century, copper was in great demand because of new technologies such as electric power that required the use of copper.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Industrial magnates fought for control of Butte's mining wealth.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Clark, Marcus Daly, James Andrew Murray and F.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Anaconda Copper Mining Company began in 1881 when Marcus Daly bought a small mine named the Anaconda.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] He was a part-owner, mine manager and engineer of the Alice, a silver mine in Walkerville, a suburb of Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] While working in the Alice, he noticed significant quantities of high-grade copper ore.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Daly obtained permission to inspect nearby workings.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After his employers, the Walker Brothers, refused to buy the Anaconda, Daly sold his interest in the Alice and bought it himself.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] He asked San Francisco mining magnate George Hearst for additional support.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Hearst agreed to buy one-fourth of the new company's stock without visiting the site.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] While mining the silver left in his mine, huge deposits of copper were soon developed and Daly became a copper magnate.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] When surrounding silver mines "played out" and closed, Daly quietly bought up the neighboring mines, forming a mining company.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] He built a smelter at Anaconda, Montana (a company town), and connected it to Butte by railway.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Anaconda Company eventually owned all the mines on Butte Hill.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Clark constructed the Copper King Mansion in Butte, which became his second residence from his home in New York City.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1899, he also purchased the Columbia Gardens, a small park he developed into an amusement park, featuring a pavilion, roller coaster, and a lake for swimming and canoeing.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Copper ore mined from the Butte mining district in 1910 alone totaled 284,000,000 pounds (129,000,000 kg); at the time, Butte was the largest producer of copper in North America and rivaled in worldwide metal production only by South Africa.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The same year, in excess of 10,000,000 troy ounces (310,000 kg) of silver and 37,000 troy ounces (1,200 kg) of gold were also discovered.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] By 1885, there were about 1,800 dues-paying members of a general union in Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] That year the union reorganized as the Butte Miners' Union (BMU), spinning off all non-miners to separate craft unions.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Some of these joined the Knights of Labor, and by 1886 the separate organizations came together to form the Silver Bow Trades and Labor Assembly, with 34 separate unions representing nearly all of the 6,000 workers around Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The BMU established branch unions in mining towns like Barker, Castle, Champion, Granite, and Neihart, and extended support to other mining camps hundreds of miles away.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1892 there was a violent strike in Coeur d'Alene.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Although the BMU was experiencing relatively friendly relations with local management, the events in Idaho were disturbing.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The BMU not only sent thousands of dollars to support the Idaho miners, they mortgaged their buildings to send more.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] There was a growing concern that local unions were vulnerable to the power of Mine Owners' Associations like the one in Coeur d'Alene.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In May 1893, about 40 delegates from northern hard-rock mining camps met in Butte and established the Western Federation of Miners (WFM), which sought to organize miners throughout the West.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Butte Miners' Union became Local Number One of the new WFM.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The WFM won a strike in Cripple Creek, Colorado, the following year, but in 1896–97 lost another violent strike in Leadville, Colorado, prompting the Montana State Trades and Labor Council to issue a proclamation to organize a new Western labor federation along industrial lines.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1899, Daly, William Rockefeller, Henry H.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Lawson organized the Amalgamated Copper Mining Company.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Not long after, the company changed its name to Anaconda Copper Mining Company (ACM).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Over the years, Anaconda was owned by assorted larger corporations.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the 1920s, it had a virtual monopoly over the mines in and around Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Between approximately 1900 and 1917, Butte also had a strong streak of Socialist politics, even electing Mayor Lewis J.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Duncan on the Socialist ticket in 1911, and again in 1913; Duncan was impeached in 1914 for neglecting duties after a bombing in the city's miners' hall in 1914.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte also established itself as "one of the most solid union cities in America." After 1905, it became a hotbed of Industrial Workers of the World (IWW, or the "Wobblies") organizing.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Rivalry between IWW supporters and the WFM locals culminated in the Butte, Montana labor riots of 1914, and resulted in the loss of union recognition by the mine owners.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After the dissolution of the Miners' Union, the Anaconda Company attempted to inaugurate programs aimed at enticing employees.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] A number of clashes between laborers, labor organizers, and the Anaconda Company ensued, including the 1917 lynching of IWW executive board officer Frank Little.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1920, company mine guards gunned down strikers in the Anaconda Road Massacre.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Seventeen were shot in the back as they tried to flee, and one man died.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Sparked by a tragic accident more than 2,000 feet (600 m) below the ground on June 8, 1917, a fire in the Granite Mountain mine shaft spewed flames, smoke, and poisonous gas through the labyrinth of tunnels including the connected Speculator Mine.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] A rescue effort commenced, but carbon monoxide was contaminating the air supply.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Several men barricaded themselves against bulkheads to save their lives, but many others died in a panic to try to escape.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Rescue workers set up a fan to prevent the fire from spreading.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] This worked for a short time, but when the rescuers tried to use water, it evaporated, creating steam that burned those trying to escape.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Once the fire had been extinguished, recovery of the deceased began; many of the bodies were mutilated beyond recognition, leaving many unidentified.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The disaster claimed a total of 168 lives.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] As of 2017, the event remained the largest hard rock mining accident in history.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Granite Mountain Memorial in Butte commemorates those who died in the accident.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Protests and strikes began after the Speculator Mine disaster, as well as the establishment of the Metal Mine Workers Union; about 15,000 workers abandoned their jobs in the disaster's wake.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] National Guard occupied Butte six times to restore civility.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1917, copper production from the Butte mines peaked and steadily declined thereafter.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] By WWII, copper production from the ACM's holdings in Chuquicamata, Chile, far exceeded Butte's production.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] She also "was instrumental in getting senate bill No.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1921, she became the first female prohibition inspector in the city.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Disputes between miners' unions and companies continued through the 1920s and 1930s, with several strikes and protests, one of which lasted for ten months in 1921.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] On New Year's Eve 1922, protestors attempted to detonate the Hibernian Hall on Main Street with dynamite.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Further industrial expansions included the arrival of the first mail plane in 1928, and in 1937, the city's streetcar system was dismantled and replaced by bus lines.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After the 1920s, the ACM began to reduce its activities in Butte due to the labor-intensivity of underground mining, as well as competition from other mine holdings in South America.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] This led the Anaconda Company to switch its focus in Butte from underground mining to open pit mining.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In response, Butte looked for ways to diversify the economy and provide employment.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The legacy of over a century of environmental degradation has, for example, produced some jobs.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Environmental cleanup in Butte, designated a Superfund site, has employed hundreds of people.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Thousands of homes were destroyed in the Meaderville suburb and surrounding areas, McQueen and East Butte, to excavate the Berkeley Pit, which Anaconda Copper opened in 1954.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] When it opened, the Berkeley Pit was the largest truck-operated open pit copper mine in the nation.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] It grew until it began encroaching on the Columbia Gardens.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After the Gardens caught fire and burned to the ground in November 1973, the Continental Pit was excavated on the former park site.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1977, the ARCO (Atlantic Richfield Company) purchased Anaconda, and three years later started shutting down mines due to lower metal prices.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1983, all mining in the Berkeley Pit was suspended.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After mining ceased at the Berkeley Pit, water pumps in nearby mines were also shut down, which resulted in highly acidic water laced with toxic heavy metals filling up the pit.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Anaconda ceased mining at the Continental Pit in 1983.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Montana Resources LLP bought the property and reopened the Continental Pit in 1986.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The company ceased mining in 2000, but resumed in 2003.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Preservation efforts of the city's historic buildings began in the late 1990s.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] As with many industrial cities, tourism and services, especially health care (Butte's St.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] James Hospital has Southwest Montana's only major trauma center), are rising as primary employers, as well as industrial-sector private companies.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] A century after the era of intensive mining and smelting, environmental issues remain in areas around the city.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Arsenic and heavy metals such as lead are found in high concentrations in some spots affected by old mining, and for a period of time in the 1990s the tap water was unsafe to drink due to poor filtration and decades-old wooden supply pipes.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Efforts to improve the water supply have taken place in the early 2000s, with millions of dollars invested to upgrade water lines and repair infrastructure.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Environmental research and cleanup efforts have contributed to the diversification of the local economy and signs of vitality, including the introduction of a multimillion-dollar polysilicon manufacturing plant nearby in the 1990s.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the late 1990s, Butte was recognized as an All-America City and as one of the National Trust for Historic Preservation's Dozen Distinctive Destinations in 2002.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Every highway exiting Butte (except westbound I-90) crosses the Divide (eastbound I-90 via Homestake Pass; eastbound MT 2 via Pipestone Pass; northbound I-15 via Elk Park Pass and southbound I-15 via Deer Lodge Pass).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city was named for a nearby landform, Big Butte, by the early miners.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte's urban landscape is notable for including mining operations set within residential areas, visible in the form of various headframes throughout the city.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The concentration of wealth in Butte due to its mining history resulted in unique and ornate architectural features among its homes and buildings, particularly in the uptown section.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Uptown, named for its steep streets, is on a hillside on the northwestern edge of the town and characterized by its abundance of lavish Victorian homes and Queen Anne style cottages built in the late 19th century.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Several of Butte's "painted ladies" homes were featured in Elizabeth Pomada's 1987 book *Daughters of Painted Ladies*.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte's South district, at a lower elevation than the hillside that comprises northern Butte, has historically been home to working-class neighborhoods.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Gold mines originally populated south Butte before it was platted for the Union Pacific Railroad in 1881.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The expansion of the Anaconda Company in the 1960s and 1970s eradicated some of Butte's historic neighborhoods, including the East Side, Dublin Gulch, Meaderville, and Chinatown.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Mary's section, which borders uptown to the east, comprised the Dublin Gulch (an enclave for Irish immigrants) and Corktown neighborhoods.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] It takes its name from the eponymous Roman Catholic parish within it, historically known as the "miner's church", scheduling masses around miners' shifting schedules.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Mary's section of Butte had a prominent population of Slavic and Finnish immigrants in addition to Irish before the mid-20th century.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte has a cold semi-arid climate (*BSk*) under the Köppen Climate Classification.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Winters are long and cold, January averaging 20.0 °F (−6.7 °C), with 30.9 nights falling below 0 °F (−18 °C) and 53.8 days failing to top freezing.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Summers are short, with very warm days and chilly nights: July averages 63.6 °F (17.6 °C).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Like most areas in this part of North America, annual precipitation is low and largely concentrated in the spring: the wettest month since precipitation records began in 1894 was June 1913, with 8.86 inches (225 mm), while no precipitation fell in September 1904.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The wettest calendar year was 1909, with 20.55 inches (522 mm) and the driest was 2021, with 6.49 inches (165 mm).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Snowfall is somewhat limited by dryness: the most in one month being 41.5 inches (1,050 mm) in May 1927 and the greatest depth on the ground 27 inches (690 mm) on December 28 and 29, 1996.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The coldest month was January 1937, with a daily mean temperature of −5.5 °F (−20.8 °C), while the coldest complete winter was 1948–49, with a three-month mean of 6.69 °F (−14.06 °C), and the mildest 1925–26, which averaged 29.21 °F (−1.55 °C).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] July 2007 was easily the hottest month, with a mean maximum of 88.8 °F (31.6 °C), although the hottest day, reaching 100 °F (38 °C), was July 22, 1931.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The coldest temperature recorded was −52 °F (−47 °C) on February 9, 1933, and December 23, 1983.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] As of the 2020 census, there were 34,494 people and 14,605 households residing in Butte-Silver Bow, giving a population density of 48.2 people per square mile (18.6 people/km2).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Per the US Census' 2019 American Community Survey, the racial makeup of the city was 94.3% White, 0.6% African American, 2.3% Native American, 0.8% Asian, 0.0% Pacific Islander, and 1.9% from two or more races.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Hispanic or Latino people of any race accounted for 4.6% of the population.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Of ethnic groups in Butte, the Irish make up a significant portion, with over one-quarter of the city's population claiming Irish descent, exceeding the percentage of Irish Americans in Boston.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Per capita, Butte has the highest percentage of Irish Americans of any city in the United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Per the 2019 American Community Survey, the average household size was 2.24 persons, 6.0% of the population is under the age of 5, 20.1% under the age of 18, and 18.7% are 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] From 2015 to 2019, the median income for a household in the city was $45,797, and 17.3% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Some sources say that Butte had a peak population of nearly 100,000 around 1920, but no documentation corroborates this, though it has been reasoned by local journalists based on city directory data.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city's population sank to a minimum around 1990 and has stabilized since then; the apparent jump in the 1980 census was due to the city's consolidation with all of Silver Bow County except Walkerville.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] As a mining boom town, Butte's economy was historically powered by its copious mining operations.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Silver and gold were initially the primary metals mined in Butte, but the abundance of copper in the area further invigorated the local economy with the advent of electricity, which created a soaring demand for the metal.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After World War I, Butte's mining economy experienced a downward trend that continued throughout the 20th century, until mining operations ceased in 1985 with the closure of the Berkeley Pit.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Over the course of its history, the city's mining operations generated over $48 billion worth of ore, making it for a time the richest city in the world.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Much of the city's economy since 2000 has been focused in energy companies (such as the Renewable Energy Corporation and NorthWestern Energy) and healthcare.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2014, NorthWestern Energy constructed a $25-million facility in uptown.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte is home to numerous museums and other educational institutions chronicling its history.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2002, Butte was one of only 12 U.S. towns to be named a Distinctive Destination by the National Trust for Historic Preservation.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Butte Silver Bow Public Library, at 226 W.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Broadway, is dedicated to preserving the town's history.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The library was created in 1894 as "an antidote to the miners' proclivity for drinking, whoring, and gambling," designed to promote middle-class values and to promote an image of Butte as a cultivated city.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Additionally, the Butte-Silver Bow Public Archives stores and provides public access to documents and artifacts from Butte's past.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Several museums and attractions are dedicated to the city's mining history, including the MBMG Mineral Museum (on the Montana Tech campus), and the World Museum of Mining, at the Orphan Girl mine in uptown Butte, which features "Hell Roarin' Gulch", a mockup of a frontier mining town.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Berkeley Pit, a gigantic former open pit copper mine, is also open to the public for viewing.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Other museums are dedicated to preserving cultural elements of Butte: The Dumas Brothel museum, a former brothel, is in Venus Alley, Butte's former historical red-light district.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Another notable site is the Rookwood Speakeasy, a prohibition-era speakeasy that features an underground city, and the Mai Wah Museum, dedicated to preserving Asian heritage in the Rocky Mountains.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The 34-room Copper King Mansion in uptown Butte was constructed in 1884 by William A.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Clark, one of the city's three Copper Kings.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The mansion functions as a bed-and-breakfast and local museum, and is often reported to be haunted.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Art Chateau, at one time home to Clark's son, Charles, was designed in the image of a French château, and houses the Butte-Silver Bow Arts Foundation.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Above Butte on the northeast edge of the city is the *Our Lady of the Rockies* statue, a 90-foot (27 m) statue of the Blessed Virgin Mary, dedicated to women and mothers everywhere, atop the Continental Divide.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The statue was airlifted to the site on December 17, 1985, after six years of construction.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] High Altitude Speed Skating Center, an outdoor speed-skating rink used as a training location for World Cup skaters.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Throughout uptown and western Butte are over ten underground mine headframes that are remnants from the town's mining industry.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] These include the Anselmo, the Steward, the Original, the Travona, the Belmont, the Kelly, the Mountain Con, the Lexington, the Bell/Diamond, the Granite Mountain, and the Badger.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] As part of a community project started around 2004, several headframes were repainted and outlined with LED lights which are illuminated at night.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte's longstanding Irish Catholic community (the largest per capita of any U.S. city) has been celebrated annually on St.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Each year, about 30,000 revelers converge on Butte's Uptown district to enjoy the parade led by the Ancient Order of Hibernians.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Also, local descendants of Finnish Americans celebrate St.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] A larger annual celebration is Evel Knievel Days, held on the last weekend of July, celebrating Evel Knievel (a Butte native).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The weekend-long event, held in Uptown Butte, features various stunt performances, sporting competitions, fundraisers, and live music.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte is perhaps becoming most renowned for the regional Montana Folk Festival held on the second weekend in July.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] This event began its run in Butte as the National Folk Festival from 2008 to 2010 and in 2011 made the transition to a free-of-admission music festival.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Also in the summer is Butte's Fourth of July Parade and Fireworks show.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2008, Barack Obama spent the last Fourth of July before his presidency campaigning in Butte, taking in the parade with his family, and celebrating his daughter Malia Obama's 10th birthday.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Pekin Noodle Parlor in Uptown is the oldest family-owned, continuously operating Chinese restaurant in the U.S.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Playing for the Pioneer Baseball League, the Butte Copper Kings were first active from 1979 to 1985, then 1987–2000; as of 2018, the team is known as the Grand Junction Rockies.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2017, the 3 Legends Stadium ballpark opened.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Hockey teams from Butte have included the Butte Irish (America West Hockey League) active from 1996 to 2002, after which they became the Wichita Falls Wildcats; and the Butte Roughriders (Northern Pacific Hockey League), active from 2003 to 2011.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Butte Cobras, a Western States Hockey League team, was active from 2014 to 2017.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Cobras then bought the Glacier Nationals franchise in the North American 3 Hockey League (NA3HL) for the 2017–18 season, but the team went dormant prior to playing the season.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] They eventually began playing in the NA3HL for the 2018–19 season.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Butte Daredevils (Continental Basketball Association), active from 2006 to 2008, were named for Butte native Evel Knievel.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] University teams include the Montana Tech Orediggers, who have competed in the Frontier Conference of the NAIA since the league's founding in 1952.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The school hosts men's and women's basketball, football, golf, and women's volleyball.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In October 2020, Butte was awarded a team in the Expedition League to begin play in May 2021.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] After the Berkeley Pit mining operation closed in 1982, pipes that pumped groundwater out of the pit were turned off, resulting in the pit slowly filling with groundwater, creating an artificial lake.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Only two years later the pit was classified as a Superfund site and an environmental hazard site.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The water in the pit is contaminated with various hard metals, such as arsenic, cadmium, and zinc.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] It was not until the 1990s that serious efforts to clean up the Berkeley Pit began.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The situation gained even more attention after as many as 342 migrating geese chose the pit lake as a resting place, resulting in their deaths.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Steps have since been taken to prevent a recurrence, including but not limited to loudspeakers broadcasting sounds to scare off waterfowl.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In November 2003, the Horseshoe Bend treatment facility went online and began treating and diverting much of the water that would have flowed into the pit.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Berkeley Pit is both a Superfund site and tourist attraction, viewable from an observation deck.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Per a 2014 report, scientists believe the Berkeley Pit may reach the critical water level—potentially contaminating Silver Bow Creek—by 2023.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Beginning in 2019, the Environmental Protection Agency ordered the Montana Resources and Atlantic Richfield Co. to begin treating water from the pit, which is to then be discharged into Silver Bow Creek at a rate of 7,000,000 US gallons (26,000,000 L) per day.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Nikia Greene, EPA project manager for mine flooding, said in 2014: "The pit is a giant bathtub.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] There's a hydraulic gradient into the pit.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Upper Clark Fork River, with Butte at the headwaters, is America's largest Superfund site, spanning 100 miles (160 km).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] This area takes in the cities of Butte, Anaconda, and Missoula.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte's mining and smelting activity resulted in significant contamination of the Butte Hill as well as downstream and downwind areas.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The contaminated land extends along a corridor of 120 miles (190 km) that reaches to Milltown and takes in adjacent areas such as the Anaconda smelter site.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Contaminated sediment flooded out from abandoned mines was the root cause of the pollution at the headwaters of the Clark Fork River.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Between the upstream city of Butte and the downstream city of Missoula lies the Deer Lodge Valley.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] By the 1970s, local citizens and agency personnel were increasingly concerned over the toxic effects of arsenic and heavy metals on environment and human health.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Anaconda Copper Mining Corporation (ACM), which merged with the Atlantic Richfield Corporation (ARCO) in 1977, is considered one of the parties responsible for the contamination.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Shortly thereafter, in 1983, ARCO ceased mining and smelting operations in the Butte-Anaconda area.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] For more than a century, the Anaconda Copper Mining company mined ore from Butte and smelted it in Butte (until c.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] During this time, the Anaconda smelter released up to 40 short tons (36 t) per day of arsenic, 1,700 short tons (1,540 t) per day of sulfur, and great quantities of lead and other heavy metals into the air.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In Butte, mine tailings were dumped directly into Silver Bow Creek, creating a 150 miles (240 km) plume of pollution extending down the valley to Milltown Dam on the Clark Fork River, just upstream of Missoula.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Air- and waterborne pollution poisoned livestock and agricultural soils throughout the Deer Lodge Valley.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Modern environmental cleanup efforts have continued into the 21st century.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1977, Butte consolidated with Silver Bow County, becoming a consolidated city-county.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] It operates under a city-county government.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Mario Micone was the last mayor of Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1977, he became the first Chief Executive of Butte-Silver Bow County.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The chief executive is a non-partisan elected position with a four-year term.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Gallagher was elected as chief executive.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Politically, Butte has historically been a Democratic stronghold, owing to its union legacy.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Likewise, Silver Bow County has historically been one of Montana's strongest Democratic bastions.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 1996, Haley Beaudry became the first Republican to represent Butte in the state legislature since 1950.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2010, Max Yates was the next Butte Republican elected to the legislature; neither Beaudry nor Yates was reelected.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2014, Butte became the third city in Montana to pass an anti-discrimination ordinance protecting LGBT residents and visitors from discrimination in employment, housing and public accommodations.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte Public Schools has two components: Butte Elementary School District and Butte High School District.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Whitehall Public Schools has two components: Whitehall Elementary School District and Whitehall High School District.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The consolidated city-county is covered by multiple school districts.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] High school districts include Butte High School District and Whitehall High School District.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] There are five elementary school districts: Butte Elementary School District, Divide Elementary School District, Melrose Elementary School District, Ramsay Elementary School District, and Whitehall Elementary School District.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte High School enrolls around 1,300 students.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In correspondence with the Butte Public Schools system, the Butte Education Foundation was established in 2006, which aims to revitalize the public schools in an effort to attract new businesses and residents.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In the foundation's mission statement, it is noted that there is a "need to demonstrate a genuine and ongoing commitment to public education.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] There are several private schools in Butte: The Butte Central Catholic High School operates under the Diocese of Helena, which also operates Butte Central Elementary, a Catholic elementary school.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Other private elementary schools include the Silver Bow Montessori School.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The first institute of higher education in Butte was the Montana School of Mines, which was established in 1889, the year of Montana's statehood.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The university changed its name to Montana Tech in the mid-20th century, and in 1994 became affiliated with the University of Montana.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The university specializes in engineering as well as geologic and hydrogeologic research.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] News & World Report* in 2017 for "Best Regional Colleges in the West." Montana Tech of the University of Montana officially changed its name to Montana Technological University in 2018.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Montana Technological University is also home to Highlands College, a two-year college that grants associate's and trade degrees.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Major AM stations in Butte are KBOW AM 550 (country) and KXTL 1370 (oldies and talk radio).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte shares its Nielsen market with nearby Bozeman, with which it forms the 194th largest TV market in the United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Prior to KWYB's sign-on, Butte received ABC from the network's then-Denver affiliate KUSA-TV in Denver, Colorado and FOX from now-defunct Butte station KBTZ.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte has one local daily, a weekly paper, as well as several papers from around the state.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] *The Montana Standard* is Butte's daily paper.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] It was founded in 1928 and is the result of *The Butte Miner* and the *Anaconda Standard* merging into one daily paper.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The *Standard* is owned by Lee Enterprises.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] *The Butte Weekly* is another local paper.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city is served by the Butte Bus system, which operates within Butte as well as to the Montana Tech campus and nearby Walkerville.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Intercity bus service is provided by Jefferson Lines and Salt Lake Express.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Bert Mooney Airport has commercial flights on Delta Connection Airlines.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte can be accessed via Interstate 15 from north–south, and Interstate 90 from east–west; the two intersect in Butte, making Butte and Billings the only cities in Montana situated at a juncture of two interstate highways.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city can also be accessed from the south via Montana Highway 2 (Old U.S.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The Union Pacific Railroad until 1971 ran the *Butte Special* from Butte, south to Idaho Falls, then to Salt Lake City.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Until 1979 Butte was served by Amtrak's Chicago – Seattle *North Coast Hiawatha* train.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The first film to notably feature Butte was *Evel Knievel* (1971), a biopic of Evel Knievel, a Butte native.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The 1976 thriller *The Killer Inside Me*, starring Stacy Keach and Susan Tyrrell and set in small-town Montana, was partially shot in Butte in September 1974.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city was featured in *Runaway Train* (1985), shot in part on the Butte, Anaconda and Pacific Railway, and in the miniseries *Return to Lonesome Dove* (1993).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Other films shot in Butte include *F.T.W.* (1994).
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The animated film *Beavis and Butt-head Do America* (1996) depicts Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2004, the Wim Wenders film *Don't Come Knocking* was set and shot in Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] In 2015, the SyFy-produced horror film *Dead 7*, which starred Nick Carter and AJ McLean of the Backstreet Boys, as well as Joey Fatone of NSYNC, was shot at the city's Anselmo Mine yards.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The 2019 film *Juanita* is set in Butte.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The city has been subject of several documentary films, including *Die Vergessene Stadt: Butte, Montana* (1992), a German documentary by Thomas Schadt, and *Butte, America* (2008), narrated by Gabriel Byrne.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] One of the earliest literary depictions of Butte was by Mary MacLane, a diarist who wrote of her life growing up in the town at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Her diaries are published under the title *I Await the Devil's Coming*, and have been credited as a progenitor of confessional writing.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Butte answers to the unflattering description of the fictional city of Poisonville in Dashiell Hammett's novel *Red Harvest*, which also alludes to the 1920 Anaconda Road Massacre.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] The 1980 novel *The Butte Polka* by Donald McCaig also incorporates the city's mining history into its plot, featuring a character who goes missing from his post at a Butte copper mine.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] More contemporary literary depictions of Butte can be found in 1998's *Buster Midnight's Cafe* by Sandra Dallas and Jon A.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Jackson's historical fiction novel *Go By Go*, which depicts the 1917 Speculator Mine disaster.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Ivan Doig's 2010 novel *Work Song* and 2013 novel *Sweet Thunder* are set in Butte in 1919 and 1920 respectively, after World War I.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Michael Corrigan's *Confessions of a Shanty Irishman* has a chapter-story set in Butte during the Speculator mining disaster and riots.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Irish writer, Kevin Barry's 2024 novel, *The Heart in Winter* draws on the history of late 19th century Butte, providing vivid depictions of the city's wild west atmosphere and characters, with particular attention to the Irish immigrants who lived there.
[src:boulder-batholith/butte-montana] Novelist Marian Jensen has published a mystery series, *Mining City Mysteries*, which is set in Butte and the surrounding region.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The **Elkhorn Mountains** are a mountain range in southwestern Montana, part of the Rocky Mountains and are roughly 300,000 acres (1200 km2) in size.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] It is an inactive volcanic mountain range with the highest point being Crow Peak at 9,414 ft (2,869 m), right next to Elkhorn Peak, 9,381 ft (2,859 m).
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The range is surrounded by the cities of Helena, Montana City, Townsend, Whitehall, and Boulder.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The majority of the range is public land including portions in the Helena-Lewis and Clark National Forest, the Beaverhead-Deerlodge National Forest, Bureau of Land Management, and state lands.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The majority of the range is in Montana's Jefferson County, while the eastern portion is in Broadwater County, Montana.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The rocks of the Elkhorns were formed about 74 to 81 million years ago (Late Cretaceous time) as a result of the Farallon tectonic plate subducting beneath western North America and allowing magma to rise to the surface.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The Elkhorn Mountains Volcanics are extrusive rocks related to the plutonic granites of the Boulder Batholith.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Fossilized dinosaurs killed by ash from the Elkhorn volcanoes have been found at Egg Mountain near Choteau, Montana.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Volcanic flows, lahars, and ash falls from sources are thickest within a radius of about 60 miles (97 km) from the Elkhorns.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The volcanics probably originally covered an area of about 100 miles (160 km) in diameter.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Mineral deposits associated with the Elkhorn Mountains Volcanics include silver mined at Elkhorn, Montana, copper mined at Butte, and gold at the Golden Sunlight Mine near Whitehall, which is associated with a breccia pipe in the volcanics.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The mountain range seen today is related to regional structural uplift dating mostly to Oligocene time.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Evidence of human settlement in the area dates back to over 12,000 years before present.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The area was included in the 1804 Louisiana Purchase.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The area was designated as common hunting ground per the Treaty with the Blackfeet of 1855.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] In the 1860s, discovery of gold brought many prospectors into the area.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Silver miners named the Elkhorn Mountains because of the large number of elk (wapati) found there.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] At its peak, the town of Elkhorn, now a ghost town, had 2500 inhabitants.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] A forest fire in 1988 burned 47,000 acres (190 km2) of the mountain range, leaving carpets of seedlings growing into new lodgepole pine forests.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] The land has been used extensively in the past for gold and silver mining, logging, and open range grazing, leaving a noticeable impact; most notably the abandoned mining town of Elkhorn.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Recently with efforts conducted by the BLM, Montana FWP and Helena National Forest, new conservation and wildlife management plans have been put into place including big horn sheep reintroduction and the westslope cutthroat trout restoration program.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Management of the 2000+ elk herd in the area and the suppression of noxious weeds is also an ongoing task.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Despite the impacts of mining, around 100,000 acres of the Elkhorns were still roadless in 1992; this included 85,000 acres of roadless National Forest land as well as adjacent BLM, state and private lands.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Congress designated 175,000 acres of the range as the "Elkhorns Wildlife Management Area," and one of Montana's most productive elk herds inhabits the range.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Because the Elkhorns are higher in elevation than the nearby section of the Continental Divide, they catch more moisture than do most other ranges east of the Divide.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] For this reason, the Elkhorns are especially diverse, with 148 documented vertebrate species.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] Tizer Basin is a SNOTEL weather station situated by Big Tizer Creek near Bullock Hill.
[src:boulder-batholith/elkhorn-mountains] 7,917 ft (2,413 m), Tizer Basin has a subalpine climate (Köppen *Dfc*).
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] A **geological map** or **geologic map** is a special-purpose map made to show various geological features.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Rock units or geologic strata are shown by color or symbols.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Bedding planes and structural features such as faults, folds, are shown with strike and dip or trend and plunge symbols which give three-dimensional orientations features.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Geological mapping is an interpretive process involving multiple types of information, from analytical data to personal observation, all synthesized and recorded by the geologist.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Geologic observations have traditionally been recorded on paper, whether on standardized note cards, in a notebook, or on a map.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Stratigraphic contour lines may be used to illustrate the surface of a selected stratum illustrating the subsurface topographic trends of the strata.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Isopach maps detail the variations in thickness of stratigraphic units.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] It is not always possible to properly show this when the strata are extremely fractured, mixed, in some discontinuities, or where they are otherwise disturbed.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Rock units are typically represented by colors.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Instead of (or in addition to) colors, certain symbols can be used.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Different geological mapping agencies and authorities have different standards for the colors and symbols to be used for rocks of differing types and ages.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Geologists take two major types of orientation measurements (using a hand compass, for example a Brunton compass): orientations of planes and orientations of lines.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Orientations of planes are measured as a "strike" and "dip", while orientations of lines are measured as a "trend" and "plunge".
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Strike and dip symbols consist of a long "strike" line, which is perpendicular to the direction of greatest slope along the surface of the bed, and a shorter "dip" line on side of the strike line where the bed is going downwards.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The angle that the bed makes with the horizontal, along the dip direction, is written next to the dip line.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] In the azimuthal system, strike and dip are often given as "strike/dip" (for example: 270/15, for a strike of west and a dip of 15 degrees below the horizontal).
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Trend and plunge are used for linear features, and their symbol is a single arrow on the map.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The arrow is oriented in the downgoing direction of the linear feature (the "trend") and at the end of the arrow, the number of degrees that the feature lies below the horizontal (the "plunge") is noted.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Trend and plunge are often notated as PLUNGE → TREND (for example: 34 → 86 indicates a feature that is angled at 34 degrees below the horizontal at an angle that is just east of true south).
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The oldest preserved geological map is the Turin papyrus (1150 BCE), which shows the location of building stone and gold deposits in Egypt.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The earliest geological map of the modern era is the 1771 "Map of Part of Auvergne, or figures of, The Current of Lava in which Prisms, Balls, Etc. are Made from Basalt.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Demarest's theories of this hard basalt.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Pasumot and Daily, Geological Engineers of the King." This map is based on Nicolas Desmarest's 1768 detailed study of the geology and eruptive history of the Auvergne volcanoes and a comparison with the columns of the Giant's Causeway of Ireland.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] He identified both landmarks as features of extinct volcanoes.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The 1768 report was incorporated in the 1771 (French) Royal Academy of Science compendium.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The first geological map of the U.S. was produced in 1809 by William Maclure.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] In 1807, Maclure undertook the self-imposed task of making a geological survey of the United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] He traversed and mapped nearly every state in the Union.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] During the rigorous two-year period of his survey, he crossed and recrossed the Allegheny Mountains some 50 times.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Maclure's map shows the distribution of five classes of rock in what are now only the eastern states of the present-day US.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The first geological map of Great Britain was created by William Smith in 1815 using principles (Smith's laws) first formulated by Smith.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Additionally, computers can now perform some tasks that were difficult to accomplish in the field, for example, handwriting or voice recognition and annotating photographs on the spot.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Digital mapping has positive and negative effects on the mapping process; only an assessment of its impact on a geological mapping project as a whole shows whether it provides a net benefit.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] With the use of computers in the field, the recording of observations and basic data management changes dramatically.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The use of digital mapping also affects when data analysis occurs in the mapping process, but does not greatly affect the process itself.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Some universities and secondary educators are integrating digital geological mapping into class work.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] For example, The GeoPad project describes the combination of technology, teaching field geology, and geological mapping in programs such as Bowling Green State University’s geology field camp.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] At Urbino University (Italy) it:Università di Urbino, Field Digital Mapping Techniques are integrated in Earth and Environmental Sciences courses since 2006 .
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The MapTeach program is designed to provide hands-on digital mapping for middle and high school students.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Digital mapping technology can be applied to traditional geological mapping, reconnaissance mapping, and surveying of geologic features.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] At international digital field data capture (DFDC) meetings, major geological surveys (e.g., British Geological Survey and Geological Survey of Canada) discuss how to harness and develop the technology.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Many other geological surveys and private companies are also designing systems to conduct scientific and applied geological mapping of, for example, geothermal springs and mine sites.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The initial cost of digital geologic computing and supporting equipment may be significant.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] In addition, equipment and software must be replaced occasionally due to damage, loss, and obsolescence.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Products moving through the market are quickly discontinued as technology and consumer interests evolve.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] A product that works well for digital mapping may not be available for purchase the following year; however, testing multiple brands and generations of equipment and software is prohibitively expensive.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Some features of digital mapping equipment are common to both survey or reconnaissance mapping and “traditional” comprehensive mapping.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The capture of less data-intensive reconnaissance mapping or survey data in the field can be accomplished by less robust databases and GIS programs, and hardware with a smaller screen size.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Hardware and software only recently (in 2000) became available that can satisfy most of the criteria necessary for digitally capturing "traditional" mapping data.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Since every geological mapping project covers an area with unique lithologies and complexities, and every geologist has a unique style of mapping, no software is perfect for digital geological mapping out of the box.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The geologist can choose to either modify their mapping style to the available software, or modify the software to their mapping style, which may require extensive programming.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] As of 2009, available geological mapping software requires some degree of customization for a given geological mapping project.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Some digital-mapping geologists/programmers have chosen to highly customize or extend ESRI's ArcGIS instead.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] At digital field data capture meetings such as at the British Geological Survey in 2002 some organisations agreed to share development experiences, and some software systems are now available to download for free.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The first geological map of Singapore was produced in 1974, produced by the then Public Work Department.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The publication includes a locality map, 8 map sheets detailing the topography and geological units, and a sheet containing cross sections of the island.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Since 1974, for 30 years, there were many findings reported in various technical conferences on newfound geology islandwide, but no new publication was produced.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] In 2006, Defence Science & Technology Agency, with their developments in underground space promptly started a re-publication of the Geology of Singapore, second edition.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The new edition that was published in 2009, contains a 1:75,000 geology map of the island, 6 maps (1:25,000) containing topography, street directory and geology, a sheet of cross section and a locality map.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The difference found between the 1976 Geology of Singapore report include numerous formations found in literature between 1976 and 2009.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] These include the Fort Canning Boulder Beds and stretches of limestone.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The United Kingdom and Isle of Man have been extensively mapped by the British Geological Survey (BGS) since 1835; a separate Geological Survey of Northern Ireland (drawing on BGS staff) has operated since 1947.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Two 1:625,000 scale maps cover the basic geology for the UK.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The 1:625,000 and 1:250,000 scales show both onshore and offshore geology (the 1:250,000 series covers the entire UK continental shelf), whilst other scales generally cover exposures on land only.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Bedrock maps (previously known as *solid* maps) show the underlying rock, without superficial deposits.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The maps are superimposed over a topographic map base produced by Ordnance Survey (OS), and use symbols to represent fault lines, strike and dip or geological units, boreholes etc.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Colors are used to represent different geological units.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Explanatory booklets (memoirs) are produced for many sheets at the 1:50,000 scale.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Small scale thematic maps (1:1,000,000 to 1:100,000) are also produced covering geochemistry, gravity anomaly, magnetic anomaly, groundwater, etc.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Although BGS maps show the British national grid reference system and employ an OS base map, sheet boundaries are not based on the grid.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The 1:50,000 sheets originate from earlier 'one inch to the mile' (1:63,360) coverage utilising the pre-grid Ordnance Survey One Inch Third Edition as the base map.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Current sheets are a mixture of modern field mapping at 1:10,000 redrawn at the 1:50,000 scale and older 1:63,360 maps reproduced on a modern base map at 1:50,000.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] In both cases the original OS Third Edition sheet margins and numbers are retained.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The 1:250,000 sheets are defined using lines of latitude and longitude, each extending 1° north-south and 2° east-west.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] In the United States, geological maps are usually superimposed over a topographic map (and at times over other base maps) with the addition of a color mask with letter symbols to represent the kind of geologic unit.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] The color mask denotes the exposure of the immediate bedrock, even if obscured by soil or other cover.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Each area of color denotes a geologic unit or particular rock formation (as more information is gathered new geologic units may be defined).
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] However, in areas where the bedrock is overlain by a significantly thick unconsolidated burden of till, terrace sediments, loess deposits, or other important feature, these are shown instead.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Stratigraphic contour lines, fault lines, strike and dip symbols, are represented with various symbols as indicated by the map key.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] Whereas topographic maps are produced by the United States Geological Survey in conjunction with the states, geological maps are usually produced by the individual states.
[src:boulder-batholith/geological-map] There are almost no geological map resources for some states, while a few states, such as Kentucky and Georgia, are extensively mapped geologically.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite is typical of a larger family of granitic rocks, or granitoids, that are composed mostly of coarse-grained quartz and feldspars in varying proportions.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] These rocks are classified by the relative percentages of quartz, alkali feldspar, and plagioclase (the QAPF classification), with true granite representing granitic rocks rich in quartz and alkali feldspar.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Most granitic rocks also contain mica or amphibole minerals, though a few (known as leucogranites) contain almost no dark minerals.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite is nearly always massive (lacking any internal structures), and tough.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] These properties have made granite a widespread construction stone throughout human history.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The word "granite" comes from the Latin *granum*, a grain, in reference to the coarse-grained structure of such a completely crystalline rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granites can be predominantly white, pink, or gray in color, depending on their mineralogy.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitic rocks mainly consist of feldspar, quartz, mica, and amphibole minerals, which form an interlocking, somewhat equigranular matrix of feldspar and quartz with scattered darker biotite mica and amphibole (often hornblende) peppering the lighter color minerals.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Occasionally some individual crystals (phenocrysts) are larger than the groundmass, in which case the texture is known as porphyritic.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A granitic rock with a porphyritic texture is known as a granite porphyry.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitoid is a general, descriptive field term for lighter-colored, coarse-grained igneous rocks.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Petrographic examination is required for identification of specific types of granitoids.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The alkali feldspar in granites is typically orthoclase or microcline and is often perthitic.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The plagioclase is typically sodium-rich oligoclase.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Phenocrysts are usually alkali feldspar.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitic rocks are classified according to the QAPF diagram for coarse grained plutonic rocks and are named according to the percentage of quartz, alkali feldspar (orthoclase, sanidine, or microcline) and plagioclase feldspar on the A-Q-P half of the diagram.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] True granite (according to modern petrologic convention) contains between 20% and 60% quartz by volume, with 35% to 90% of the total feldspar consisting of alkali feldspar.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitic rocks poorer in quartz are classified as syenites or monzonites, while granitic rocks dominated by plagioclase are classified as granodiorites or tonalites.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitic rocks with alkali feldspar comprising over 90% of the total feldspar are classified as alkali feldspar granites.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitic rock with more than 60% quartz, which is uncommon, is classified simply as quartz-rich granitoid or, if composed almost entirely of quartz, as quartzolite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] True granites are further classified by the percentage of their total feldspar that is alkali feldspar.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A granite containing 15% to 25% quartz and whose feldspar is 65% to 90% alkali feldspar is syenogranite, while the feldspar in monzogranite is 35% to 65% alkali feldspar.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A granite containing both muscovite and biotite micas is called a binary or *two-mica* granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Two-mica granites are typically high in potassium and low in plagioclase, and are usually S-type granites or A-type granites, as described below.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Another aspect of granite classification is the ratios of metals that potentially form feldspars.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Most granites have a composition such that almost all their aluminum and alkali metals (sodium and potassium) are combined as feldspar.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This is the case when K2O + Na2O + CaO > Al2O3 > K2O + Na2O.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Such granites are described as *normal* or *metaluminous*.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granites in which there is not enough aluminum to combine with all the alkali oxides as feldspar (Al2O3 < K2O + Na2O) are described as *peralkaline*, and they contain unusual sodium amphiboles such as riebeckite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granites in which there is an excess of aluminum beyond what can be taken up in feldspars (Al2O3 > CaO + K2O + Na2O) are described as *peraluminous*, and they contain aluminum-rich minerals such as muscovite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The average density of granite is between 2.65 and 2.75 g/cm3 (165 and 172 lb/cu ft), its compressive strength usually lies above 200 MPa (29,000 psi), and its viscosity near STP is 3–6·1020 Pa·s.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The melting temperature of dry granite at ambient pressure is 1215–1260 °C (2219–2300 °F); it is strongly reduced in the presence of water, down to 650 °C at a few hundred megapascals of pressure.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite has poor primary permeability overall, but strong secondary permeability through cracks and fractures if they are present.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The medium-grained equivalent of granite is **microgranite**.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The extrusive igneous rock equivalent of granite is rhyolite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitic rock is widely distributed throughout the continental crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Much of it was intruded during the Precambrian age; it is the most abundant basement rock that underlies the relatively thin sedimentary veneer of the continents.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Outcrops of granite tend to form tors, domes or bornhardts, and rounded massifs.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granites sometimes occur in circular depressions surrounded by a range of hills, formed by the metamorphic aureole or hornfels.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite often occurs as relatively small, less than 100 km2 stock masses (stocks) and in batholiths that are often associated with orogenic mountain ranges.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Small dikes of granitic composition called aplites are often associated with the margins of granitic intrusions.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In some locations, very coarse-grained pegmatite masses occur with granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite forms from silica-rich (felsic) magmas.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Felsic magmas are thought to form by addition of heat or water vapor to rock of the lower crust, rather than by decompression of mantle rock, as is the case with basaltic magmas.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] It has also been suggested that some granites found at convergent boundaries between tectonic plates, where oceanic crust subducts below continental crust, were formed from sediments subducted with the oceanic plate.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The melted sediments would have produced magma intermediate in its silica content, which became further enriched in silica as it rose through the overlying crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Early fractional crystallisation serves to reduce a melt in magnesium and chromium, and enrich the melt in iron, sodium, potassium, aluminum, and silicon.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Further fractionation reduces the content of iron, calcium, and titanium.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This is reflected in the high content of alkali feldspar and quartz in granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The presence of granitic rock in island arcs shows that fractional crystallization alone can convert a basaltic magma to a granitic magma, but the quantities produced are small.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] For example, granitic rock makes up just 4% of the exposures in the South Sandwich Islands.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In continental arc settings, granitic rocks are the most common plutonic rocks, and batholiths composed of these rock types extend the entire length of the arc.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] There are no indication of magma chambers where basaltic magmas differentiate into granites, or of cumulates produced by mafic crystals settling out of the magma.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Other processes must produce these great volumes of felsic magma.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] One such process is injection of basaltic magma into the lower crust, followed by differentiation, which leaves any cumulates in the mantle.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Another is heating of the lower crust by underplating basaltic magma, which produces felsic magma directly from crustal rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The two processes produce different kinds of granites, which may be reflected in the division between S-type (produced by underplating) and I-type (produced by injection and differentiation) granites, discussed below.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The composition and origin of any magma that differentiates into granite leave certain petrological evidence as to what the granite's parental rock was.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The final texture and composition of a granite are generally distinctive as to its parental rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] For instance, a granite that is derived from partial melting of metasedimentary rocks may have more alkali feldspar, whereas a granite derived from partial melting of metaigneous rocks may be richer in plagioclase.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] It is on this basis that the modern "alphabet" classification schemes are based.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The letter-based Chappell & White classification system was proposed initially to divide granites into I-type (igneous source) granite and S-type (sedimentary sources).
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Both types are produced by partial melting of crustal rocks, either metaigneous rocks or metasedimentary rocks.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] I-type granites are characterized by a high content of sodium and calcium, and by a strontium isotope ratio, 87Sr/86Sr, of less than 0.708.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] 87Sr is produced by radioactive decay of 87Rb, and since rubidium is concentrated in the crust relative to the mantle, a low ratio suggests origin in the mantle.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The elevated sodium and calcium favor crystallization of hornblende rather than biotite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] I-type granites are known for their porphyry copper deposits.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] I-type granites are orogenic (associated with mountain building) and usually metaluminous.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] S-type granites are sodium-poor and aluminum-rich.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As a result, they contain micas such as biotite and muscovite instead of hornblende.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Their strontium isotope ratio is typically greater than 0.708, suggesting a crustal origin.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] They also commonly contain xenoliths of metamorphosed sedimentary rock, and host tin ores.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Their magmas are water-rich, and they readily solidify as the water outgasses from the magma at lower pressure, so they less commonly make it to the surface than magmas of I-type granites, which are thus more common as volcanic rock (rhyolite).
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] They are also orogenic but range from metaluminous to strongly peraluminous.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Although both I- and S-type granites are orogenic, I-type granites are more common close to the convergent boundary than S-type.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This is attributed to thicker crust further from the boundary, which results in more crustal melting.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] These granites are produced by partial melting of refractory lithology such as granulites in the lower continental crust at high thermal gradients.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This leads to significant extraction of hydrous felsic melts from granulite-facies resitites.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A-type granites occur in the Koettlitz Glacier Alkaline Province in the Royal Society Range, Antarctica.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The rhyolites of the Yellowstone Caldera are examples of volcanic equivalents of A-type granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] M-type granite was later proposed to cover those granites that were clearly sourced from crystallized mafic magmas, generally sourced from the mantle.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Although the fractional crystallisation of basaltic melts can yield small amounts of granites, which are sometimes found in island arcs, such granites must occur together with large amounts of basaltic rocks.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] H-type granites were suggested for hybrid granites, which were hypothesized to form by mixing between mafic and felsic from different sources, such as M-type and S-type.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] However, the big difference in rheology between mafic and felsic magmas makes this process problematic in nature.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granitization is an old, and largely discounted, hypothesis that granite is formed in place through extreme metasomatism.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The idea behind granitization was that fluids would supposedly bring in elements such as potassium, and remove others, such as calcium, to transform a metamorphic rock into granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This was supposed to occur across a migrating front.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] However, experimental work had established by the 1960s that granites were of igneous origin.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The mineralogical and chemical features of granite can be explained only by crystal-liquid phase relations, showing that there must have been at least enough melting to mobilize the magma.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] However, at sufficiently deep crustal levels, the distinction between metamorphism and crustal melting itself becomes vague.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Conditions for crystallization of liquid magma are close enough to those of high-grade metamorphism that the rocks often bear a close resemblance.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Under these conditions, granitic melts can be produced in place through the partial melting of metamorphic rocks by extracting melt-mobile elements such as potassium and silicon into the melts but leaving others such as calcium and iron in granulite residues.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A migmatite consists of dark, refractory rock (the *melanosome*) that is permeated by sheets and channels of light granitic rock (the *leucosome*).
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The leucosome is interpreted as partial melt of a parent rock that has begun to separate from the remaining solid residue (the melanosome).
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] If enough partial melt is produced, it will separate from the source rock, become more highly evolved through fractional crystallization during its ascent toward the surface, and become the magmatic parent of granitic rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The residue of the source rock becomes a granulite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The partial melting of solid rocks requires high temperatures and the addition of water or other volatiles which lower the solidus temperature (temperature at which partial melting commences) of these rocks.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] It was long debated whether crustal thickening in orogens (mountain belts along convergent boundaries) was sufficient to produce granite melts by radiogenic heating, but recent work suggests that this is not a viable mechanism.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In-situ granitization requires heating by the asthenospheric mantle or by underplating with mantle-derived magmas.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite magmas have a density of 2.4 Mg/m3, much less than the 2.8 Mg/m3 of high-grade metamorphic rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This gives them tremendous buoyancy, so that ascent of the magma is inevitable once enough magma has accumulated.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] However, the question of precisely how such large quantities of magma are able to shove aside country rock to make room for themselves (the *room problem*) is still a matter of research.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Of these two mechanisms, Stokes diapirism has been favoured for many years in the absence of a reasonable alternative.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The basic idea is that magma will rise through the crust as a single mass through buoyancy.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As it rises, it heats the wall rocks, causing them to behave as a power-law fluid and thus flow around the intrusion allowing it to pass without major heat loss.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This is entirely feasible in the warm, ductile lower crust where rocks are easily deformed, but runs into problems in the upper crust which is far colder and more brittle.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Rocks there do not deform so easily: for magma to rise as a diapir it would expend far too much energy in heating wall rocks, thus cooling and solidifying before reaching higher levels within the crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Fracture propagation is the mechanism preferred by many geologists as it largely eliminates the major problems of moving a huge mass of magma through cold brittle crust.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Magma rises instead in small channels along self-propagating dykes which form along new or pre-existing fracture or fault systems and networks of active shear zones.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As these narrow conduits open, the first magma to enter solidifies and provides a form of insulation for later magma.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] For example, diapirs may continue to rise through the brittle upper crust through stoping, where the granite cracks the roof rocks, removing blocks of the overlying crust which then sink to the bottom of the diapir while the magma rises to take their place.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Evidence for piecemeal stoping is found in intrusions that are rimmed with *igneous breccia* containing fragments of country rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Assimilation is another mechanism of ascent, where the granite melts its way up into the crust and removes overlying material in this way.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This is limited by the amount of thermal energy available, which must be replenished by crystallization of higher-melting minerals in the magma.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Thus, the magma is melting crustal rock at its roof while simultaneously crystallizing at its base.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This results in steady contamination with crustal material as the magma rises.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This may not be evident in the major and minor element chemistry, since the minerals most likely to crystallize at the base of the chamber are the same ones that would crystallize anyway, but crustal assimilation is detectable in isotope ratios.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Heat loss to the country rock means that ascent by assimilation is limited to distance similar to the height of the magma chamber.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Physical weathering occurs on a large scale in the form of exfoliation joints, which are the result of granite's expanding and fracturing as pressure is relieved when overlying material is removed by erosion or other processes.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Chemical weathering of granite occurs when dilute carbonic acid, and other acids present in rain and soil waters, alter feldspar in a process called hydrolysis.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As demonstrated in the following reaction, this causes potassium feldspar to form kaolinite, with potassium ions, bicarbonate, and silica in solution as byproducts.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] An end product of granite weathering is grus, which is often made up of coarse-grained fragments of disintegrated granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Climatic variations also influence the weathering rate of granites.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] For about two thousand years, the relief engravings on Cleopatra's Needle obelisk had survived the arid conditions of its origin before its transfer to London.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Within two hundred years, the red granite has drastically deteriorated in the damp and polluted air there.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Soil development on granite reflects the rock's high quartz content and dearth of available bases, with the base-poor status predisposing the soil to acidification and podzolization in cool humid climates as the weather-resistant quartz yields much sand.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Feldspars also weather slowly in cool climes, allowing sand to dominate the fine-earth fraction.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In warm humid regions, the weathering of feldspar as described above is accelerated so as to allow a much higher proportion of clay with the Cecil soil series a prime example of the consequent Ultisol great soil group.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Fires can also contribute to the weathering of granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The high temperatures reached during a fire—often exceeding 1000 °C—can cause significant physical and chemical processes that alter the rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Additionally, the decomposition of certain granite constituents, such as phyllosilicates, at specific temperatures further contributes to granite degradation.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As a result, granite becomes micro-fractured, its total porosity increases, and its mechanical strength is significantly reduced.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite is a natural source of radiation, like most natural stones.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Potassium-40 is a radioactive isotope of weak emission, and a constituent of alkali feldspar, which in turn is a common component of granitic rocks, more abundant in alkali feldspar granite and syenites.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Some granites contain around 10 to 20 parts per million (ppm) of uranium.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] By contrast, more mafic rocks, such as tonalite, gabbro and diorite, have 1 to 5 ppm uranium, and limestones and sedimentary rocks usually have equally low amounts.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Many large granite plutons are sources for palaeochannel-hosted or roll front uranium ore deposits, where the uranium washes into the sediments from the granite uplands and associated, often highly radioactive pegmatites.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Cellars and basements built into soils over granite can become a trap for radon gas, which is formed by the decay of uranium.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Radon gas poses significant health concerns and is the number two cause of lung cancer in the US behind smoking.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Conway granite has been noted for its relatively high thorium concentration of 56±6 ppm.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] There is some concern that some granite sold as countertops or building material may be hazardous to health.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Johns University has stated that approximately 5% of all granite is of concern, with the caveat that only a tiny percentage of the tens of thousands of granite slab types have been tested.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Resources from national geological survey organizations are accessible online to assist in assessing the risk factors in granite country and design rules relating, in particular, to preventing accumulation of radon gas in enclosed basements and dwellings.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A study of granite countertops was done (initiated and paid for by the Marble Institute of America) in November 2008 by National Health and Engineering Inc. of USA.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite and related marble industries are considered one of the oldest industries in the world, existing as far back as Ancient Egypt.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Major modern exporters of granite include China, India, Italy, Brazil, Canada, Germany, Sweden, Spain and the United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The term "granite" is a vague term in the construction industry as it usually includes other intrusive rocks such as gabbro and diorite besides true granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] 2590 BC), named for the light crimson hue of its exposed limestone surfaces, is the third largest of Egyptian pyramids.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Pyramid of Menkaure, likely dating 2510 BC, was constructed of limestone and granite blocks.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] 2580 BC) contains a granite sarcophagus fashioned of "Red Aswan Granite".
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The mostly ruined Black Pyramid dating from the reign of Amenemhat III once had a polished granite pyramidion or capstone, which is now on display in the main hall of the Egyptian Museum in Cairo (see Dahshur).
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Other uses in Ancient Egypt include columns, door lintels, sills, jambs, and wall and floor veneer.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] How the Egyptians worked the solid granite is still a matter of debate.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Tool marks described by the Egyptologist Anna Serotta indicate the use of flint tools on finer work with harder stones, e.g. when producing the hieroglyphic inscriptions.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Patrick Hunt has postulated that the Egyptians used emery, which has greater hardness.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The Seokguram Grotto in Korea is a Buddhist shrine and part of the Bulguksa temple complex.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Completed in 774 AD, it is an artificial grotto constructed entirely of granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The main Buddha of the grotto is a highly regarded piece of Buddhist art, and along with the temple complex to which it belongs, Seokguram was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1995.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Rajaraja Chola I of the Chola Dynasty in South India built the world's first temple entirely of granite in the 11th century AD in Tanjore, India.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The Brihadeeswarar Temple dedicated to Lord Shiva was built in 1010.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The massive Gopuram (ornate, upper section of shrine) is believed to have a mass of around 81 tonnes.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] It was the tallest temple in south India.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Imperial Roman granite was quarried mainly in Egypt, and also in Turkey, and on the islands of Elba and Giglio.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite became "an integral part of the Roman language of monumental architecture".
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The quarrying ceased around the third century AD.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Beginning in Late Antiquity the granite was reused, which since at least the early 16th century became known as spolia.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Through the process of case-hardening, granite becomes harder with age.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The technology required to make tempered metal chisels was largely forgotten during the Middle Ages.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As a result, Medieval stoneworkers were forced to use saws or emery to shorten ancient columns or hack them into discs.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In some areas, granite is used for gravestones and memorials.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite is a hard stone and requires skill to carve by hand.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Until the early 18th century, in the Western world, granite could be carved only by hand tools with generally poor results.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A key breakthrough was the invention of steam-powered cutting and dressing tools by Alexander MacDonald of Aberdeen, inspired by seeing ancient Egyptian granite carvings.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In 1832, the first polished tombstone of Aberdeen granite to be erected in an English cemetery was installed at Kensal Green Cemetery.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] It caused a sensation in the London monumental trade and for some years all polished granite ordered came from MacDonald's.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] As a result of the work of sculptor William Leslie, and later Sidney Field, granite memorials became a major status symbol in Victorian Britain.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The royal sarcophagus at Frogmore was probably the pinnacle of its work, and at 30 tons one of the largest.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] It was not until the 1880s that rival machinery and works could compete with the MacDonald works.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Modern methods of carving include using computer-controlled rotary bits and sandblasting over a rubber stencil.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Leaving the letters, numbers, and emblems exposed and the remainder of the stone covered with rubber, the blaster can create virtually any kind of artwork or epitaph.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The stone known as "black granite" is usually gabbro, which has a completely different chemical composition.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite has been extensively used as a dimension stone and as flooring tiles in public and commercial buildings and monuments.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Aberdeen in Scotland, which is constructed principally from local granite, is known as "The Granite City".
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Because of its abundance in New England, granite was commonly used to build foundations for homes there.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The Granite Railway, America's first railroad, was built to haul granite from the quarries in Quincy, Massachusetts, to the Neponset River in the 1820s.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Engineers have traditionally used polished granite surface plates to establish a plane of reference, since they are relatively impervious, inflexible, and maintain good dimensional stability.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Sandblasted concrete with a heavy aggregate content has an appearance similar to rough granite, and is often used as a substitute when use of real granite is impractical.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite tables are used extensively as bases or even as the entire structural body of optical instruments, CMMs, and very high precision CNC machines because of granite's rigidity, high dimensional stability, and excellent vibration characteristics.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] A most unusual use of granite was as the material of the tracks of the Haytor Granite Tramway, Devon, England, in 1820.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite block is usually processed into slabs, which can be cut and shaped by a cutting center.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In military engineering, Finland planted granite boulders along its Mannerheim Line to block invasion by Russian tanks in the Winter War of 1939–40.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] This is because it is extremely durable, permeable and requires little maintenance.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] For example, in Sydney, Australia black granite stone is used for the paving and kerbs throughout the Central Business District.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite can be crushed using industrial equipment such as VSI or cone crusher.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Curling stones are traditionally fashioned of Ailsa Craig granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] The first stones were made in the 1750s, the original source being Ailsa Craig in Scotland.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Because of the rarity of this granite, the best stones can cost as much as US$1,500.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Between 60 and 70 percent of the stones used today are made from Ailsa Craig granite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Although the island is now a wildlife reserve, it is still quarried under license for Ailsa granite by Kays of Scotland for curling stones.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] In the United States, granite is a popular choice for countertops due to its affordability, aesthetic appeal, and convenience.
[src:boulder-batholith/granite] Granite is one of the rocks most prized by climbers, for its steepness, soundness, crack systems, and friction.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The term **banatite** is sometimes used informally for various rocks ranging from granite to diorite, including granodiorite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The term *granodiorite* was first used by G.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Becker (1893) to describe granitic rocks in the Sierra Nevada, United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] According to the QAPF diagram, granodiorite has a greater than 20% quartz by volume, and between 65% and 90% of the feldspar is plagioclase.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] A greater amount of plagioclase would designate the rock as tonalite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Granodiorite is felsic to intermediate in composition.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] It is the intrusive igneous equivalent of the extrusive igneous dacite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] It contains a large amount of sodium (Na) and calcium (Ca) rich plagioclase, potassium feldspar, quartz, and minor amounts of muscovite mica as the lighter colored mineral components.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Amphiboles (often in the form of hornblende), and biotite are more abundant in granodiorite than in granite, giving it a more distinct two-toned or overall darker appearance.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Mica may be present in well-formed hexagonal crystals, and hornblende may appear as needle-like crystals.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Minor amounts of oxide minerals such as magnetite, ilmenite, and ulvöspinel, as well as some sulfide minerals may also be present.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] On average, the upper continental crust has the same composition as granodiorite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Granodiorite is a plutonic igneous rock, formed by intrusion of silica-rich magma, which cools in batholiths or stocks below the Earth's surface.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] It is usually only exposed at the surface after uplift and erosion have occurred.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The name comes from two related rocks to which granodiorite is an intermediate: granite and diorite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The *gran-* root comes from the Latin *grānum* for "grain", an English language derivative.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Diorite is named after the contrasting colors of the rock.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Banatite is a term used informally for various rocks ranging from granite to diorite, but often granodiorite, that were intruded in the Late Cretaceous in the Banat and nearby regions of present-day Hungary and Serbia.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The term is also used in Australia in connection with Gulaga / Mount Dromedary in New South Wales, where it is described as "a rock of intermediate composition between quartz diorite and quartz monzonite".
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Plymouth Rock is a glacial erratic boulder of granodiorite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The Sierra Nevada mountains contain large sections of granodiorite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Granodiorite was quarried at Mons Claudianus in the Red Sea Governorate in eastern Egypt from the 1st century AD to the mid-3rd century AD.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Much of the quarried stone was transported to Rome for use in major projects such as the Pantheon and Hadrian's Villa.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Additionally, granodiorite was used for the Rosetta Stone.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The extent of Egyptian granodiorite masonry is unclear.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Egypt's 6000-year history makes determining the period of usage difficult as well.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Perhaps like porphyry, it was ignored by the successive dynasties of Egypt and only heavily mined during Ptolemaic or Roman times.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] This is evidenced by the fact that most examples of granodiorite sculpture seem to have come from later dates.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] However, its presence in the Rosetta Stone implies that they had considerable experience with it and the fact that only newer artifacts are found may simply be because earlier pieces were lost.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Granodiorite is quarried in the Newry area of County Armagh with the common name of 'Newry granite'.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] Granodiorite is most often used as crushed stone for road building.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] It is also used as construction material, building facade, and paving, and as an ornamental stone.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The Rosetta Stone is a stele made from granodiorite.
[src:boulder-batholith/granodiorite] The portico columns of the Pantheon in Rome are formed from single shafts of granodiorite, each 12 metres tall by 1.5 metres in diameter.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena was founded as a gold camp during the Montana gold rush on July 14, 1864, following the discovery of gold at Last Chance Gulch by the Four Georgians.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It was formally established on October 30, 1864.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Due to the gold rush, Helena became a wealthy city, with approximately 50 millionaires inhabiting the area by 1888.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The concentration of wealth contributed to the city's prominent, elaborate Victorian architecture.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] At the 2020 census Helena's population was 32,091, making it the 5th least populous state capital in the United States and the 6th most populous city in Montana.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It is the principal city of the Helena Metropolitan Statistical Area, which includes all of Lewis and Clark, and Jefferson counties; the MSA's population being 83,058 according to the 2020 census.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The local daily newspaper is the *Independent Record*.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The city is served by Helena Regional Airport (HLN).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Helena area was long inhabited by various indigenous peoples.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Evidence from the MacHaffie and Indian Creek sites on opposite sides of the Elkhorn Mountains southeast of the Helena Valley show that people of the Folsom culture lived in the area more than 10,000 years ago.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Before the introduction of the horse 300 years ago, and since, other native peoples, including the Salish and the Blackfeet, visited the area seasonally on their nomadic rounds.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] By the early 1800s, people of European descent from the United States and British Canada began arriving to work the streams of the Missouri River watershed looking for fur-bearing animals such as the beaver, undoubtedly bringing them through the area now known as the Helena Valley.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Gold strikes in Idaho Territory in the early 1860s attracted many migrants who initiated major gold rushes at Grasshopper Creek (Bannack) and Alder Gulch (Virginia City) in 1862 and 1863 respectively.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] So many people came that the federal government created a new territory called Montana in May 1864.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The miners prospected far and wide for new placer gold discoveries.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] On July 14, 1864, the discovery of gold by a prospecting party known as the "Four Georgians" in a gulch off the Prickly Pear Creek led to the founding of a mining camp along a small creek in the area they called "Last Chance Gulch".
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In the 1870s, a Pennsylvania brick and stonemason named Louis Reeder built Reeder's Alley.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It is a strong link to the beginnings of the settlement.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] He invested in the lots along then Cutler Street (now known as Reeder's Alley) and between 1872 and 1884 built over 30 brick and stone one-room tenements for miners.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In 1876, Thomas Cruse, a prospector of Irish descent, discovered a massive gold deposit in the mountains, northwest of Helena.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] He soon filed a mining patent on 20.25 acres and opened the famous Drumlummon Mine which produced a rich bounty of gold and silver worth millions of dollars.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] By fall of 1864, the population had grown to over 200, and some thought the name "Last Chance" was too crass.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] On October 30, 1864, a group of at least seven self-appointed men met to name the town, authorize the layout of the streets, and elect commissioners.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The first suggestion was "Tomah", a word the committee thought had connections to the local Indian people.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Other nominations included Pumpkinville and Squashtown (as the meeting was held the day before Halloween).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Other suggestions were to name the community after various Minnesota towns, such as Winona and Rochester, as a number of settlers had come from Minnesota.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Finally, a Scotsman, John Summerville, proposed *Helena*, which he pronounced /həˈliːnə/ *hə-LEE-nə*, in honor of Helena Township, Scott County, Minnesota.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] This immediately caused an uproar from the former Confederates in the room, who insisted upon the pronunciation /ˈhɛlɪnə/ *HEL-i-nə*, after Helena, Arkansas, a town on the Mississippi River.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] While the name "Helena" won, the pronunciation varied until approximately 1882 when the /ˈhɛlɪnə/ *HEL-i-nə* pronunciation became dominant.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Later tales of the naming of Helena claimed the name came from the island of St.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena, where Napoleon was exiled, or was that of a miner's sweetheart.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena was surveyed by Captain John Wood in 1865 for the first time.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The original streets of Helena followed the paths of miners, thus making the city blocks of Early Helena various sizes and shapes.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Washburn, having been appointed Surveyor General of Montana in 1869, organized the Washburn-Langford-Doane Expedition in Helena to explore the regions that would become Yellowstone National Park.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Mount Washburn, within the park, is named for him.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] By 1888 about 50 millionaires lived in Helena, more per capita than in any city in the world.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It is estimated about $3.6 billion in today's money was extracted from Helena during this period of time.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Last Chance Placer is one of the most famous placer deposits in the western United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Most of the production occurred before 1868.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Much of the placer is now under Helena's streets and buildings.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] This large concentration of wealth was the basis of developing fine residences and ambitious architecture in the city; its Victorian neighborhoods reflect the gold years.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The numerous miners also attracted the development of a thriving red light district.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Among the well-known local madams was Josephine "Chicago Joe" Airey, who built a thriving business empire between 1874 and 1893, becoming one of Helena's largest and most influential landowners.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena's brothels were a successful part of the local business community well into the 20th century, ending with the 1973 death of Helena's last madam, "Big Dorothy" Baker.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena's official symbol is a drawing of "The Guardian of the Gulch", a wooden fire watch tower built in 1886.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It still stands on Tower Hill overlooking the downtown district.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The tower, built in 1874, replaced a series of observation buildings, the original being built in response to a series of devastating fires that swept through the early mining camp.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] On August 2, 2016, an arson attack severely damaged the tower and it was deemed structurally unstable.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The tower is to be demolished but will be rebuilt using the same methods as in its original construction.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In 1889, railroad magnate Charles Arthur Broadwater opened his Hotel Broadwater and Natatorium west of Helena.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Natatorium was home to the world's first indoor swimming pool.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Damaged in the 1935 Helena earthquake, it closed in 1941.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The property's many buildings were demolished in 1976.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Today, the Broadwater Fitness Center stands just west of the Hotel & Natatorium's original location, complete with an outdoor pool heated by natural spring water running underneath it.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena has been the capital of Montana Territory since 1875 and the state of Montana since 1889.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Referendums were held in 1892 and 1894 to determine the state's capital; the result was to keep the capitol in Helena.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In 1902, the Montana State Capitol was completed.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Until the 1900 census, Helena was the most populous city in the state.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] That year it was surpassed by Butte (with a population of 30,470), where mining industry was developing.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Among the settlers the city's prosperity attracted were Blacks fleeing racism in the South.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Many found work in the mines or on the railroads and established a middle class that supported Black-owned businesses, Black churches, Black newspapers and a Black literary society.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] A Black police officer patrolled the town's wealthiest (white) neighborhood.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In 1916, the United Daughters of the Confederacy commissioned the construction of the Confederate Memorial Fountain in Hill Park.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It was the only Confederate memorial in the Northwestern United States.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The fountain was removed on August 18, 2017, after the Helena City Commission deemed it a threat to public safety following a white nationalist rally in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Archie Bray Foundation, a ceramics center founded in 1952, is just northwest of Helena, near Spring Meadow Lake.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Cathedral of Saint Helena and the Helena Civic Center are two of Helena's many significant historic buildings.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 18%) work for agencies of the state government.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] When in Helena, most people visit the local walking mall.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It was completed in the early 1980s after Urban Renewal and the Model Cities Program in the early 1970s had removed many historic buildings from the downtown district.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] During the next decade, a three-block shopping district was renovated that followed the original Last Chance Gulch.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] A small artificial stream runs along most of the walking mall to represent the underground springs that originally flowed above ground in parts of the Gulch.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In September 1983, the EPA proposed that an approximately 8.4 acre site in East Helena be listed on the Superfund National Priorities List because of a zinc and lead smelting facility had been emitting heavy metals like arsenic, lead, and cadmium into the air and soil for almost a century.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Following thorough testing of soil, groundwater, and biological samples (blood, stool, and hair) from local residents, the results showed that residents of East Helena, especially children under seven, recorded significantly higher blood lead levels than those of the average Montana population.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Thus, the East Helena site was officially listed in June 1984 and continues to undergo regular remediation and monitoring activities in coordination with the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and the Center for Disease Control (CDC).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] With the mountains, Helena has much outdoor recreation, including hunting and fishing.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Great Divide Ski Area is northwest of town near the ghost town of Marysville.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena is also known for its mountain biking.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] It was officially designated as an International Mountain Bicycling Association bronze level Ride Center on October 23, 2013.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena High School and Capital High School are public high schools in Helena School District No.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In 2017, Helena voters elected as mayor former Liberian refugee Wilmot Collins, who was widely reported to be Helena's first black mayor.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The *Independent Record* reported contested research indicating that in the early 1870s one E.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Johnson, listed in the city directory as a black barber from Washington D.C., had been elected mayor, before Helena became an incorporated town.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 16.39 square miles (42.45 km2), of which 16.35 square miles (42.35 km2) is land and 0.04 square miles (0.10 km2) is water.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena has a semi-arid climate (Köppen *BSk*), with long, cold and moderately snowy winters, hot and dry summers, and short springs and autumns in between.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Snowfall has been observed in every month but July, but is usually absent from May to September, and normally accumulates in only light amounts.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Winters have periods of moderation, partly due to warming influence from chinooks.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Precipitation mostly falls in the spring and is generally sparse, averaging only 11.4 inches (290 mm) annually.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The hottest temperature recorded in Helena was 105 °F (41 °C) on August 24, 1969, and July 15, 2002, while the coldest temperature recorded was −42 °F (−41 °C) on January 31, 1893, January 25, 1957, and February 2, 1996.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] As of the 2020 census, Helena had a population of 32,091.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 19.3% of residents were under the age of 18 and 20.7% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] For every 100 females there were 91.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 89.7 males age 18 and over.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 98.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 1.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 14,924 households in Helena, of which 22.6% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Of all households, 36.2% were married-couple households, 23.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 32.8% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] About 40.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 15,902 housing units, of which 6.2% were vacant.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.5% and the rental vacancy rate was 5.3%.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] As of the census of 2010, there were 28,190 people, 12,780 households, and 6,691 families residing in the city.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The population density was 1,724.2 inhabitants per square mile (665.7/km2).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 13,457 housing units at an average density of 823.1 units per square mile (317.8 units/km2).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The racial makeup of the city was 93.3% White, 0.4% African American, 2.3% Native American, 0.7% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 0.6% from other races, and 2.6% from two or more races.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.8% of the population.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 12,780 households, of which 24.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were married couples living together, 10.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.6% had a male householder with no wife present, and 47.6% were non-families.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 39.8% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The average household size was 2.07 and the average family size was 2.77.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The median age in the city was 40.3 years.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 20.1% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.6% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 23.3% were from 25 to 44; 29.5% were from 45 to 64; and 15.6% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The gender makeup of the city was 48.0% male and 52.0% female.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] As of the census of 2000, there were 25,780 people, 11,541 households, and 6,474 families residing in the city.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The population density was 1,840.7 people per square mile (710.7 people/km2).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 12,133 housing units at an average density of 866.3 units per square mile (334.5 units/km2).
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The ethnic makeup of the city is 94.8% White, 0.2% African American, 2.1% Native American, 0.8% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 0.4% from other races, and 1.7% from two or more races.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 1.7% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 11,541 households, out of which 27.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.5% were married couples living together, 10.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 43.9% were non-families.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] 37.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The average household size was 2.14 and the average family size was 2.83.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] In the city, the population was spread out, with 22.4% under the age of 18, 11.1% from 18 to 24, 26.6% from 25 to 44, 26.0% from 45 to 64, and 13.9% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] For every 100 females, there were 91.0 males.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.6 males.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The median income for a household in the city was $34,416, and the median income for a family was $50,018.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Males had a median income of $34,357 versus $25,821 for females.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The per capita income for the city was $20,020.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] About 9.3% of families and 14.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 16.4% of those under age 18 and 8.3% of those age 65 or over.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena has a long record of economic stability with its history as being the state capital and being founded in an area rich in silver and lead deposits.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] However, this situation has resulted in a slow growing economy.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Its status as capital makes it a major hub of activity at the county, state, and federal level.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] According to the Helena Area Chamber of Commerce, the capital's median household income is $50,889, and its unemployment rate stood at 3.8% in 2013, about 1.2% lower than the rest of the state.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Education is a major employer, with two high schools and accompanying elementary and middle schools for K–12 students as well as Helena College.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Major private employers within the city of Helena include Carroll College and the medical community.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena's economy is also bolstered by Fort William Henry Harrison, the training facility for the Montana National Guard, located just outside the city.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Fort Harrison is also home to Fort Harrison VA Medical Center, where many Helena-area residents work.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Several school districts provide public education from pre-kindergarten to 12th grade.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Helena Public School District has two components: Helena Elementary School District and Helena High School District.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Almost all of Helena is in Helena Elementary School District and Helena High School District.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Helena Elementary School District consists of 13 schools covering students from pre-kindergarten to 8th grade.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] There were 5,181 students enrolled in the district during the 2021–2022 school year.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] The Helena High School District has two schools for students in 9th through 12th grade.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena High School had 1,128 students enrolled for the 2021–2022 school year while Capital High School had 1,350.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena's public library is the main branch of the Lewis & Clark Library.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Branches are also in Augusta, East Helena, and Lincoln.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena has a mayor and four city commissioners.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] They each are elected to four year terms.
[src:boulder-batholith/helena-montana] Helena's Designated Market Area is 205th in size, as defined by Nielsen Media Research, and is the fifth smallest media market in the nation.
